04245nam a22006015i 9780292795617DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927956177 a10.7560/7134442doi  a(DE-B1597)587093  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1993.5.U6bD47 2006eb 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4309732221 aDillon, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Solaris Effect :bArt and Artifice in Contemporary American Film /cSteven Dillon. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Tarkovsky’s Solaris and the Cinematic Abyss -- t2 Steven Soderbergh’s TintedWorld -- t3 Aronofsky, Sundance, and the Return to Nature -- t4 Mulholland Drive, Cahiers du cinéma, and the Horror of Cinephilia -- t5 Spielberg’s A.I.: Animation, Time, and Digital Culture -- t6 Cinema against Art: Artists and Paintings in Contemporary American Film -- t7 A Plague of Frogs: Expressionism and Naturalism in 1990s American Film -- t8 Situating American Film in Godard, Jarmusch, and Scorsese -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat do contemporary American movies and directors have to say about the relationship between nature and art? How do science fiction films like Steven Spielberg's A.I. and Darren Aronofsky's π represent the apparent oppositions between nature and culture, wild and tame? Steven Dillon's intriguing new volume surveys American cinema from 1990 to 2002 with substantial descriptions of sixty films, emphasizing small-budget independent American film. Directors studied include Steven Soderbergh, Darren Aronofsky, Todd Haynes, Harmony Korine, and Gus Van Sant, as well as more canonical figures like Martin Scorcese, Robert Altman, David Lynch, and Steven Spielberg. The book takes its title and inspiration from Andrei Tarkovsky's 1972 film Solaris, a science fiction ghost story that relentlessly explores the relationship between the powers of nature and art. The author argues that American film has the best chance of aesthetic success when it acknowledges that a film is actually a film. The best American movies tell an endless ghost story, as they perform the agonizing nearness and distance of the cinematic image. This groundbreaking commentary examines the rarely seen bridge between select American film directors and their typically more adventurous European counterparts. Filmmakers such as Lynch and Soderbergh are cross-cut together with Tarkovsky and the great French director, Jean-Luc Godard, in order to test the limits and possibilities of American film. Both enthusiastically cinephilic and fiercely critical, this book puts a decade of U.S. film in its global place, as part of an ongoing conversation on nature and art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMotion pictureszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795617/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK